# First-Run Questionnaire

When starting a brand new development session with no prior context (user hasn't specified what to work on, or explicitly asks to "set up" / "get started" / "initialize"), run through these batched AskQuestion calls to capture preferences.

**Skip this if the user already has a specific task.** Only run when bootstrapping a new session or when explicitly requested.

## Batch 1: Session Identity

```
AskQuestion({
 title: "Session Setup - What Are We Building?",
 questions: [
 {
 id: "domain",
 prompt: "What area of openclaw are we working on today?",
 options: [
 { id: "cli", label: "CLI commands / flags" },
 { id: "gateway", label: "Gateway / server runtime" },
 { id: "channels", label: "Messaging channels (Telegram, Discord, Signal, etc.)" },
 { id: "extensions", label: "Extensions / plugins" },
 { id: "apps", label: "Native apps (macOS, iOS, Android)" },
 { id: "web-ui", label: "Web UI / provider-web" },
 { id: "infra", label: "Infrastructure / CI / Docker" },
 { id: "docs", label: "Documentation" },
 { id: "testing", label: "Test coverage / test infrastructure" },
 { id: "bug", label: "Bug fix / investigation" },
 { id: "pr-review", label: "PR review / landing" },
 { id: "custom", label: "Other (type below)" }
 ]
 },
 {
 id: "scope",
 prompt: "How big is this effort?",
 options: [
 { id: "quick", label: "Quick fix (< 30 min)" },
 { id: "feature", label: "Feature / enhancement (1-3 hours)" },
 { id: "epic", label: "Large effort / multi-session" },
 { id: "explore", label: "Just exploring / learning the codebase" }
 ]
 }
 ]
})
```

## Batch 2: Risk & Mutation Policy

```
AskQuestion({
 title: "Session Setup - Safety Preferences",
 questions: [
 {
 id: "mutation",
 prompt: "How aggressive should I be with changes?",
 options: [
 { id: "auto-safe", label: "Auto-apply safe changes, ask for risky ones (recommended)" },
 { id: "propose-all", label: "Propose all changes as diffs first" },
 { id: "full-auto", label: "Full auto - just do it, I'll review at the end" },
 { id: "read-only", label: "Read-only - analysis and suggestions only" }
 ]
 },
 {
 id: "testing",
 prompt: "Should I run tests after changes?",
 options: [
 { id: "always", label: "Always run related tests after changes" },
 { id: "ask", label: "Ask me before running tests" },
 { id: "end", label: "Run tests at the end of the session only" },
 { id: "skip", label: "Skip tests (I'll run them manually)" }
 ]
 }
 ]
})
```

## Batch 3: Development Style

```
AskQuestion({
 title: "Session Setup - Development Style",
 questions: [
 {
 id: "commits",
 prompt: "How should I handle commits?",
 options: [
 { id: "ask-each", label: "Ask before each commit" },
 { id: "bundle", label: "Bundle changes and commit at logical checkpoints" },
 { id: "end-only", label: "Only commit when I explicitly ask" },
 { id: "never", label: "Don't commit - I'll handle git myself" }
 ]
 },
 {
 id: "verbosity",
 prompt: "How verbose should explanations be?",
 options: [
 { id: "terse", label: "Terse - just the code and minimal context" },
 { id: "moderate", label: "Moderate - brief explanations of key decisions" },
 { id: "detailed", label: "Detailed - explain reasoning and alternatives" }
 ]
 }
 ]
})
```

## After Collection

Store the answers mentally for the session and adjust behavior accordingly. Reference them when making decisions about:
- Whether to auto-apply vs propose
- When to run tests
- How to handle git operations
- How much explanation to provide

These preferences carry through the entire session until explicitly changed.
